    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-02-10T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-02-10T00:00:00-05:00" n="750"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d750">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">832.802 Lloyd Brasileiro Navigation Co./50</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Brazil</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morgan</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-02-10">February 10,
                            1932</date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1707</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>A copy of the air mail despatch addressed to the Secretary of State on December
                    11, 1931, by the Ambassador at Rio de Janeiro regarding a discount of fifty per
                    cent on consular fees to shippers by the Lloyd Brasileiro Navigation Company,
                    was forwarded for their information to the United States Shipping Board on
                    January 20, 1932. There is enclosed for the information of the Embassy a copy of
                    a reply dated February 4, 1932, from the Chairman of the Shipping Board,<note
                        n="6" xml:id="d750fn6">Not printed.</note> in which the statement will be
                    observed that, because of the comments in the Embassy’s despatch regarding the
                    possibility of retaliatory measures, the matter will be given further careful
                    consideration by the Shipping Board and if it should be decided to proceed under
                    the provisions of Section 26 of the Shipping Act of 1916, a further
                    communication on the subject will be addressed to the Department.</p>
                <closer>[File copy not signed]</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
